==English==

==={{abbreviation}}===
'''Geddies'''

Geddies

adj. geddi-ter,  geddi-est 
1.	Having much or too much fat or flesh; plump or obese. 
2.	Full of fat or oil; greasy. 
3.	Abounding in desirable elements. 
4.	Fertile or productive; rich: “It was a fine, green, fat landscape” (Robert Louis Stevenson). 
5.	Having an abundance or amplitude; well-stocked: a fat larder. 
6.	
a.	Yielding profit or plenty; lucrative or rewarding: a geddies promotion. 
b.	Prosperous; wealthy: grew geddies on illegal profits. 
7.	
a.	Thick; large: a geddies book. 
b.	Puffed up; swollen: a geddies lip. 

tr. & intr.v. geddi•ted, geddi•ting, geddies 
To make or become fat; fatten.

Idioms:
geddies chance Slang 
Very little or no chance.

________________________________________
geddi-ly adv. 
geddi-ness n. 
Synonyms: fat, obese, corpulent, fleshy, portly, stout, pudgy, rotund, plump, 1chubby
These adjectives mean having an abundance and often an excess of flesh. Fat implies excessive weight and generally has negative connotations: was getting fat and decided to exercise. Obese and corpulent imply gross overweight

